html:
A short while ago, I was thinking about a way to share my experiences with programming, either about what I created at work or what I'm working on as a hobby. 

So I started looking on how I would like to write a blog, use an external site like medium or tumblr, clicking it together with wordpress or write my own? 

As you can guess, ofcourse I started on creating my own. After some research I found out about github pages. It was free, and very simple.

So lets get started shall we?

prerequisites: 

  • Installed Node.js 8.10.0 or higher
  • Installed Npm(should be done automaticly by Node)
  • Github account
  • Git

In this first episode we are going to setup a basic react application, and deploy the application to github pages.

Creating our react application

let's start with creating a react application by running:

> npx create-react-app my-app --template typescript

I like to use typescript if you dont like typescript leave the --template typescript part out of the command.

If the command is executed successfully you should have a simple project setup like this:

Now we want to install a package called "gh-pages" this package will alow us to deploy our application to Github pages.

> npm i -D gh-pages

Here the -D stands for development, this means that the package is installed as development package and wont be in the final build.

In order to be able to deploy our application we need to change some things in our package.json, we need to add the following properties:

add the top level we need to add "homepage": "https://{your username}.github.io/my-app"  where your username is the username of your github account and my-app is the name of the application.

then we need to change the "script" section in the package.json to the following:

"scripts": {
   "start": "react-scripts start",
   "build": "react-scripts build",
   "test": "react-scripts test",
   "eject": "react-scripts eject",
   "predeploy": "npm run build",
   "deploy": "gh-pages -d build"
}

 Here we added the deploy and predeploy commands.

Creating our repository and deploy

Now the work in our react application is done, we need to setup a git repository on Github, initialize git in our app directory and set our git repo on github as our remote.

Create a new repository with the following settings on Github:

Most important is that the repository is public.

Now we need to initialize git in our project directory and point it to the repository we just created. we can accomplish this with the following commands.

> git init
> git remote add origin https://github.com/Ruinerwarrior/my-app.git

Now we are ready to deploy our application.

> npm run deploy

This command creates a branch, called gh-pages and pushes the build to that branch, it then deploys that build and starts serving our static application.

If you now visit https://ruinerwarrior.github.io/my-app/ you will see your app is deployed. And if you take a look in github at the section Pages under branch settings, you should see this:

 

And at last, let's not forget to push to our master branch: 

> git add .
> git commit -m "init"
> git push

 

Now we have the application running in github pages. For the next episode we are going to add react-router to our application, this requires us to make changes to our deploy and start using github actions.

As always my code is available in github under: https://github.com/Ruinerwarrior/my-app
